<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV REVIEW; IN 'SIRENS,' HIGH-CONCEPT COPS FOUNDER ON THE ROCKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WILLMAN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 That's "Sirens" as in fabulous babes -- vis-a-vis the title of a new 
syndicated series about female cops -- and, of course, "Sirens" as in lights. 
But will it be "Sirens" as in luring viewers onto the rocks? It's there, in 
that third definition, that the high-concept breaks down a bit. 
</P>
<P>
 The opening scene lives up (or down) to what you'd expect out of this premise: 
A gorgeous gal in uniform angrily enters a quizzical hunk's apartment and 
announces, "You have the right to take your clothes off," adding, as she strips 
down to black lingerie, "Anything you touch can and will be used against you." 
</P>
<P>
 Oh, Miranda! 
</P>
<P>
 But, for better or worse, the prurience level flags sharply thereafter. Turns 
out these are two married cops celebrating their anniversary, and the 
postcoital mood is shattered mere minutes later when the husband is gunned down 
on the street, leaving his blond widow, Jessie (Jayne Heitmeyer), to go 
sleuthing for his assassin, most likely a murderous fellow peace officer. 
</P>
<P>
 Along the way, Jessie bonds with Lynn (Adrienne-Joi Johnson) and Molly (Liza 
Snyder), as we know she will, since the silly opening credits feature these 
three performing synchronized, model-type moves together. (A fourth female cop, 
Ellen Cohen, also joins in the camaraderie but isn't included among the series' 
principals.) 
</P>
<P>
 But the series isn't nearly as campy as it promises, or probably needs, to be. 
Amazingly, this two-part opener (which continues next week) wants to hew closer 
to "Hill Street Blues" or "Homicide," what with its hand-held camera work, than 
to "Charlie's Angels." 
</P>
<P>
 These aspirations hardly hold up in a story whose mystery villain is 
telegraphed almost from the start and whose gritty dialogue includes zingers 
like "Real good -- for a woman!" and "Degenerate male-chauvinist pig!" The glam 
cast does its admirable best to make this credible, but any scripting they 
touch can and will be used against them. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Sirens" premieres at 9 tonight on KCOP-TV Channel 13.  
</P>
</TEXT>
