<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS AMIGOS SCORES FOUR TOUCHDOWNS IN 13 MINUTES, BEATS SANTA ANA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE McKIBBEN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Los Amigos Coach Roger Takahashi had planned to unleash the right arm of 
quarterback Ape Tuato on Thursday night against Santa Ana. But before Takahashi 
got a chance to look at his game plan, the game was over. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Amigos scored four touchdowns in the first 13 minutes and rolled to a 41-0 
victory over Santa Ana in front of about 750 at Garden Grove High. Tuato got in 
some work, completing five of seven passes for 97 yards and a touchdown, but it 
wasn't enough for Takahashi. 
</P>
<P>
 "I know we can throw the ball because we did it well over the summer," 
Takahashi said. "Ape could have had a big game passing, but it got so out of 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to be balanced, but right now we are just rushing well. We're going 
to need to throw when we get to big games and the playoffs." 
</P>
<P>
 Los Amigos (3-0) doesn't figure to have a big game until Oct. 14, when it 
plays at Rancho Alamitos. Until then, Tuato probably will have to get his 
throwing done before halftime. 
</P>
<P>
 Lobo running back Greg Fausto scored three touchdowns and ran for 97 yards in 
11 carries before backup Roger Calvillo took over. Calvillo rushed seven times 
for 78 yards and a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
 "We know Roger has the ability," Takahashi said. "He's more of a power runner 
than Greg. We might be able to use him on short yardage situations in the 
future." 
</P>
<P>
 There were few short-yardage situations Thursday night, though. The Lobos 
never punted and scored on six of their first seven possessions. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, Santa Ana (0-3) fumbled twice, had one pass intercepted, never 
crossed the Los Amigos 20-yard line and failed on five of six fourth-down 
situations. 
</P>
<P>
 Running back Omar Gomez was the lone bright spot, rushing for 72 yards in 17 
carries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
