<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE NFL; RYAN INTERESTED IN SIGNING PHIL 
SIMMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Buddy Ryan, yet to win with the Arizona Cardinals or settle on a quarterback, 
now says he's interested in Phil Simms. "I've got a call into him right now," 
the coach said after practice.While the Cardinals consider Simms, they have 
closed the door on Rich Gannon. Ryan says he will not pursue the former starter 
at Minnesota and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
 In another personnel matter, Ryan said he will sign running back Barry Word if 
Word checks out medically. Word, 31, arrived at the training facility 
unannounced Wednesday and worked out for coaches after practice. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The NFL and its game officials reached a tentative agreement on a new contract 
that will increase salaries by nearly 50% and triple pension payments. NFL 
spokesman Joe Browne confirmed the nine-member board of directors of the 
officials association has unanimously agreed to a settlement pending a mail 
vote of all 101 game officials. It's expected to be completed by Tuesday. . . . 
The Washington Redskins lead the NFL with a payroll of $46.997 million, 
including pro-rated bonuses and player benefits, according to figures released 
by the NFL Players Assn. The numbers also show that 18 of the 28 teams are 
actually over the $34.6-million salary cap when pro-rated bonuses are included. 
Teams under the cap include Dallas, Miami and the New York Giants. . . . The 
Giants released wide receiver Mark Jackson to make room for waiver-wire pickup 
Coleman Rudolph. It marked the second time this year that the Giants released 
Jackson, their leading receiver in 1993. Jackson was waived in a salary-cap 
move in May, but was re-signed in training camp and made the roster as the 
backup to Mike Sherrard and Chris Calloway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
