<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAUGUS GETS THROWN FOR A 23-0 LOSS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANA HADDAD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saugus High had the third-stingiest defense among Southern Section teams in 
the Valley area. Loyola had allowed only 14 points in its first two games. 
</P>
<P>
 Something had to give when these unbeaten teams met Thursday night at Canyon 
High. The Saugus defensive backfield gave -- generously -- in a 23-0 rout by 
the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
 Loyola quarterback Kyle Spielbuhler threw three long touchdown passes against 
a Centurion defense that refused to bend against the rush but was short-handed 
in the secondary without injured cornerbacks Mark Beatty and Jeff D'Amico. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have no excuses, though," Saugus Coach Jack Bowman said. "We blew three 
coverages." 
</P>
<P>
 The three touchdowns, plus a safety, all came in the first half. The 
Centurions (2-1), despite holding the Cubs to 100 yards rushing in 30 attempts 
(22 yards in the first half), couldn't stop Spielbuhler and his receiving 
corps. 
</P>
<P>
 The Loyola quarterback completed 11 of 13 passes for 194 yards. Midway through 
the first quarter, Spielbuhler hit Dan Farmer on a fade pattern. Farmer, 
6-feet-4, 200 pounds, blew past 5-8, 156-pound cornerback Pat Rafter for a 
36-yard touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
 The Cubs made it 9-0 when Brandon Alvarado's punt was blocked in the end zone 
by Loyola's Soren Solari. Centurion Mark Pecaro recovered for the safety. 
</P>
<P>
 After the free kick, Loyola marched 66 yards in five plays, scoring on a 
42-yard pass play from Spielbuhler to Patrick Klein for a 16-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think one of our strengths is our wideouts," Loyola Coach Steve Grady said. 
"They're tall, strong and good athletes." 
</P>
<P>
 Farmer, who had five receptions for 104 yards and two touchdowns, scored again 
when Loyola surprised the Centurions on a 46-yard pass play with 15 seconds 
left in the first half after lining up without a huddle. 
</P>
<P>
 No defender was within 15 yards of Farmer when he caught the ball along the 
left sideline. 
</P>
<P>
 Saugus quarterback Kevin Carrasco completed only seven of 23 passes for 66 
yards and was sacked four times. 
</P>
<P>
 STILL UNBEATEN: Nordhoff High improved to 3-0 with an 18-7 nonleague victory 
over St. Bonaventure. C10 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Prep Sports; Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA092394-0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 081876 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
