<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIDELINES; VENTURA DEVELOPING A HEALTHY APPETITE FOR WINNING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Guess who's coming to dinner tonight? 
</P>
<P>
 The Ventura College football team. And, for the second week in a row, the 
players will eat for free. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week, Coach George Rosales picked up the tab, making good on his promise 
to treat defensive players to a steak dinner each time they post a shutout. 
</P>
<P>
 He had no reason to believe his promise was risky business. Ventura last 
season was 0-10 and allowed an average of 33.5 points a game. There were 
shutouts -- six of them -- but the Pirates were on the wrong end each time. 
</P>
<P>
 Times have changed. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura defeated West L.A., 38-0, in its opener two weeks ago. The defense 
cashed in the following Friday, eating at a restaurant owned by Charles 
(Buster) Davis, a former Pirate defensive end. The cost of feeding about 45 
players was $100 because Davis gave the coaches a significant discount. 
</P>
<P>
 Then Davis offered an even sweeter deal. For each victory, the entire Ventura 
team -- about 90 players -- could eat dinner for free. 
</P>
<P>
 "Those guys don't have a lot of money and a square meal is heavenly," said 
Davis, who played for the Pirates in 1968 and '69 and then transferred to Cal 
State Long Beach, where he was converted to a tight end. "I understand that, 
being a former player." 
</P>
<P>
 Davis' fortunes have changed since his playing days. Certainly, Ventura's have 
changed in Rosales' second season. 
</P>
<P>
 The Pirates won again last week, defeating Antelope Valley, 20-12. 
</P>
<P>
 Now Davis has circled Nov. 12 on his calendar. That's the date Ventura plays 
host to Moorpark. 
</P>
<P>
 Isaiah Mustafa, Davis' stepson, is a wide receiver for the Raiders. 
</P>
<P>
 Watch, listen, attack: Steve Copping is willing to lend a helping hand. 
</P>
<P>
 Just be careful how you grab it. 
</P>
<P>
 Copping has coached jujitsu at Harvard-Westlake High since he established the 
school's program in 1984. The team, which competes against other martial arts 
clubs, includes 30 students who specialize in one or more of jujitsu's 25 
sub-arts -- including judo, tai chi and meditation. 
</P>
<P>
 Copping is ranked fifth in the world by the World Council of Jujitsu 
Organizations. On Saturdays, he offers free martial arts workshops, from 9 a.m. 
to noon, at Harvard-Westlake's Studio City campus. 
</P>
<P>
 "People can watch, they can talk to instructors, they can work out," said 
Copping, who has been teaching for 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
 Little big Manny: If Manny Marquez ever makes a game-winning kick for the Cal 
State Northridge football team, it will take only one teammate to hoist him up 
and carry him off the field. The freshman from Bishop Diego High in Santa 
Barbara is only 5-foot-2, 140 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Small, but mighty. Though he is second on the depth chart for conversion kicks 
and field-goal duties, Marquez already is the Matadors' top man for kickoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 "He has a very live and creditable leg," Burt said. "Corey Pavin hits a golf 
ball a long way. It's not always about size." 
</P>
<P>
 Showtime: The Saugus High football team battled touted Loyola on Thursday 
night, but this afternoon the Centurions will suit up again and play a mock 
game on their home field in front of a director and a motion-picture camera 
crew. 
</P>
<P>
 Saugus Coach Jack Bowman has no details about the project other than a Santa 
Clarita-based production company selected his team for an episode of a 
children's show called "V.R. Troopers." Stats  
</P>
<P>
 The Newbury Park High football team has won 21 consecutive games against 
Ventura County teams. Over that span, which started in the sixth week of the 
1991 season, the Panthers are 28-3 -- their losses coming against San Marcos, 
Agoura and Nogales. 
</P>
<P>
 Overall, the Panthers have won 16 in a row, including last year's 14-0 
Southern Section championship campaign. 
</P>
<P>
 Catching on: With 11 more receptions, Brian Comer will become Valley College's 
all-time pass-catching leader. 
</P>
<P>
 The sophomore from Chatsworth High has 74 receptions, including 16 this season 
for 278 yards and three touchdowns. Rob Mattram had 84 receptions in the 1970 
and '71 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
 Grounded: Palmdale High's football team has scored only six points in two 
games, ineptitude that can directly be traced to the Falcons' running game -- 
or lack thereof. Palmdale has gained two yards in 37 carries. 
</P>
<P>
 Falcons take heart. It could be worse. Palmdale's ground game is twice as 
productive as that of El Camino Real's, which has gained one yard. St. 
Genevieve, which has lost 10 yards, and Poly, which has lost 16, are in the 
hole. 
</P>
<P>
 Path of little resistance: The 352-yards rushing Di-Onte Smith accumulated for 
Grant against Marshall last Friday probably is a school record. 
</P>
<P>
 However, it is not even the most yardage Marshall has allowed in the past two 
seasons. Tennell Young, then a junior at Eagle Rock, rushed for 393 yards and 
five touchdowns in a 35-7 victory over Marshall last year. Things to Do  
</P>
<P>
 Today, 3 p.m., through Saturday, Ventura High and Ventura College swimming 
pools: Buena High plays host to a 16-team tournament featuring five of the top 
10 high school water polo teams in the Southern Section Division IV. 
</P>
<P>
 Compiled by Mike Hiserman. Contributing: Fernando Dominguez, Steve Elling, 
Jeff Fletcher, Vince Kowalick, Michael Lazarus and John Ortega. 
</P>
</TEXT>
