<P>
 Ex-Broker for Prudential Settles SEC Charges: Peggy Jean Homuth, 35, a former 
broker who worked in Prudential Securities' Rochester, N.Y., office for 10 
years, has agreed to settle Securities and Exchange Commission charges that she 
forged clients' signatures and bilked them out of $3.2 million.She also could 
face a prison term of up to 41 months and fines of up to $75,000 after pleading 
guilty to related federal mail fraud charges. The settlement orders Homuth to 
pay $3.2 million, an amount the SEC said "she took from her customers," plus 
prejudgment interest. The payment was waived, however, because she lacks the 
funds. 
