<HEADLINE>
<P>
FED SAYS ECONOMY IS SLOWING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Bloomberg Business News 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 U.S. economic growth is "clearly slowing" from its pace earlier in the year, 
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Greenspan said it's "still unclear" as to how much of a slowdown is in 
progress. 
</P>
<P>
 At the same time, the Fed chairman said there are signs that product and labor 
markets are approaching capacity limits. The Fed is examining these signs for 
"evidences of pressures" that inflation is about to accelerate. 
</P>
<P>
 Greenspan's comments, at a hearing by the Senate Banking Committee, come as 
the Fed's Open Market Committee prepares to meet Tuesday to set interest rate 
policy for the weeks ahead. 
</P>
<P>
 Economists are divided over whether the committee will vote to raise key 
lending rates next week or wait until after the November Congressional 
elections. In previous moves this year, the Fed pushed the federal funds rate 
on loans among banks to 4.75% from 3%, and the discount rate on direct loans to 
banks to 4% from 3%. 
</P>
</TEXT>
