<HEADLINE>
<P>
TALKS UNDERWAY ON PLAN FOR HEADLANDS; DEVELOPMENT: DANA POINT CONSERVATION 
GROUP AND LANDOWNERS ARE DISCUSSING THE SALE OF 21 OF THE 121 ACRES AND SCALING 
BACK THE $500-MILLION PROJECT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEN HALL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Private discussions are taking place that could save part of the 121-acre Dana 
Point Headlands from development and perhaps affect a bitter environmental 
fight over one of the most controversial projects in South County. 
</P>
<P>
 The owners of the property overlooking Dana Point Harbor and a local 
conservation group are discussing a plan to sell some of the land to the Dana 
Point Headlands Conservancy and scale back the $500-million development 
project, participants in the talks confirmed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Conservancy officials said a key element of the plan calls for their group to 
buy about nine acres of the most prominent, environmentally sensitive land at 
the tip of the peninsula, including the habitat of the endangered Pacific 
pocket mouse. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, the conservancy would have a five-year option to buy an 
additional 12 acres, which is now the proposed location of a 400-room luxury 
hotel. 
</P>
<P>
 The landowner could then develop the residential portion of the project, 
currently proposed as 370 homes on property with sweeping views up and down the 
coast, conservancy officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Two members of the fledgling Dana Point Headlands Conservancy said a 
representative of the landowners approached them to discuss the potential deal. 
</P>
<P>
 "The property is for sale, all of it, in five sections . . . so it might as 
well be to the citizens of Dana Point," said Jacqueline Cain, a conservancy 
director. "That's the last remaining open space in Dana Point and if it's 
built, it's gone forever. It's irreplaceable." Another director, Ernest A. 
Nelson, said he is "optimistic" that the talks can lead to an agreement over 
the headlands. 
</P>
<P>
 "We started out not knowing what our chances would be to win an agreement with 
the landowners, but now (they're) talking," Nelson said. "It's still a long 
shot, but it can happen, it really can." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 An appraisal on the nine acres at the tip of the peninsula is being obtained 
by the landowners, the Newport Beach-based M.H. Sherman Co. and the 
Pasadena-based Chandis Securities Co., a partnership that has owned the 
property since the 1940s. (Chandis Securities, a firm that oversees the 
financial holdings of the Chandler family, is a major stockholder in Times 
Mirror Co., publisher of the Los Angeles Times.) 
</P>
<P>
 Dan T. Daniels, president of M.H. Sherman Co., acknowledged the talks but 
stopped short of calling the discussions an effort toward compromise. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have had discussions with these folks and that's all we've done," Daniels 
said. "The conservancy has asked us for an option on a lot of the property. We 
are having an appraisal done to see if they are serious." 
</P>
<P>
 Approved last April by the Dana Point City Council, the project has been the 
target of protests by residents who claim the development is too extensive and 
will destroy one of the last major undeveloped coastal properties in the 
county. 
</P>
<P>
 The headlands peninsula was noted by New England author Richard Henry Dana in 
1835 in his book "Two Years Before the Mast." The city was named after Dana 
when it was subdivided in the 1920s. 
</P>
<P>
 The approved plan for the Headlands is the subject of two heated citywide 
November ballot measures that could force the council to rescind its approval 
of the project. 
</P>
<P>
 Conservancy official Nelson said he met this week with aides for three South 
County legislators -- Assemblyman William Morrow (R-Oceanside), state Sen. 
William Craven (R-Oceanside) and state Sen. Marian Bergeson (R-Newport Beach) 
-- to outline the group's effort to obtain the property. 
</P>
<P>
 Nelson and Cain said that because the headlands property contains habitat for 
endangered species such as the cactus wren and California gnatcatcher, federal 
funds are available to help buy the land. A citywide bond issue could be 
another potential source of purchase money, they said. 
</P>
<P>
 Nelson said there are no exact figures for the purchase, and little money has 
been raised so far. But the conservancy believes "we need to be able to 
generate $40 million to $50 million," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Money aside, conservancy officials said there are two keys to achieving a 
compromise: The property must be affordable and the City Council must accept 
the plan even though the 400-room luxury hotel would not be built. Conservancy 
officials say the council, with its eyes on the potential $2-million annual bed 
tax revenue the hotel would generate, is the driving force behind the hotel 
portion of the project, not the landowners. 
</P>
<P>
 "This was something the council wanted and something the resident supporters 
of the project were touting as the main benefit of this project," said 
Councilman William L. Ossenmacher, an opponent of the proposed development. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Councilwoman Karen Lloreda, one of the project's supporters, agreed. 
</P>
<P>
 "As a council person, one of my concerns has always been and continues to be 
revenues to the city," Lloreda said. "I don't have a problem with a scaled-down 
version of the hotel, but I believe there is valuable revenue available to the 
city from this headlands project and I would hate to see that disappear." 
</P>
<P>
 Lloreda added that the California Coastal Commission has insisted in the past 
that coastal development projects include facilities -- such as hotels -- that 
can be used by the general public. Simply providing open space has not been 
enough, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 But Lloreda also said she believes there is still plenty of room for 
compromise. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are three issues here: the property owners' needs, the city's needs and 
the people's needs," she said. "Perhaps the developer is going to have to give 
up a little bit of the housing (element of the plan). There is room for 
everybody to compromise here." Headlands Talks The Dana Point Headlands 
Conservacy is exploring the purchase of a prime portion of the 121-acre 
headlands property-currently marked for a 400-room luxury hotel, residential 
and commercial development. The deal would include an initial nine-acre plot 
with an option for 12 more acres. 
</P>
