<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: PLACENTIA; CITY TO EQUIP PATROL CARS WITH COMPUTER 
TERMINALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HOLLY J. WAGNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Placentia City Council has approved a $69,333 expenditure for Mobile Data 
Terminals for the city's 15 police patrol cars. 
</P>
<P>
 The dashboard-mounted computer keyboards and display screens are touted as a 
way to improve officer safety by keeping radio calls off the airwaves, where 
they can be intercepted by anyone monitoring the Police Department's radio 
frequencies. 
</P>
<P>
 The terminals also will let officers check for warrants and stolen car 
information before stopping a car, saving time and alerting the officer to 
potential criminal drivers. 
</P>
<P>
 According to Police Chief Manuel Ortega, neighboring cities that have 
installed the terminals are able to recover more stolen autos and arrest more 
wanted suspects by avoiding the verbal broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
 The system will enable officers in the patrol cars to communicate with 
colleagues at other locations and with police dispatchers through computer 
messages similar to e-mail. They will also be able to write reports in the 
field, saving transcription time and keeping more officers on the street.HOLLY 
J. WAGNER 
</P>
</TEXT>
