<HEADLINE>
<P>
O.C. CONFIDENCE IN ECONOMY HITS HIGHEST IN '90S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WOODYARD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Orange County consumers are regaining their faith in the economy and now boast 
the highest confidence levels of the 1990s, according to a UC Irvine report 
released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 The latest Orange County Annual Survey pegged the local Consumer Confidence 
Index at 89, a level just below the national average and a whopping 16 points 
higher than last year. The local index is now at its highest in four years. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is one important indication that Orange County has come out of 
recession," said Esmael Adibi, an economist at Chapman University in Orange. 
</P>
<P>
 The 1994 survey, conducted by Prof. Mark Baldassare at the UC Irvine School of 
Social Ecology, found a sharp increase in the number of adults who said that 
they are better off now than a year ago. Consumers also generally believe the 
nation has a prosperous year ahead and that now is a good time to buy 
big-ticket items such as cars and refrigerators. 
</P>
<P>
 Those results are significant, Adibi and other analysts said, because they 
suggest that consumers will start making big purchases that they had put off 
during the recession. And that buying spree, in turn, will create jobs in 
manufacturing and retail. 
</P>
<P>
 "Consumer spending looks like it's ready to take off," said UCI research 
associate Cheryl Katz, who conducted the survey with Baldassare. "We will see 
more spending across the board, more home buying, perhaps." Also, she said, 
people will be "generally more at ease with their finances." 
</P>
<P>
 Some retailers say they are already seeing signs of freer spending. Auto 
dealers, for example, report that their business has picked up, with some 
having sold out their entire inventories. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't have a single '94 Jeep on the lot," said Gary Gray, owner of Orange 
Coast Jeep Eagle in Coast Mesa. "Last year at this time, I had 150 '93 Jeeps 
that I couldn't sell." 
</P>
<P>
 The consumer confidence report also bodes well for the holidays, retailers' 
busiest season and thus a crucial part of their fiscal year. Yet it does not 
mean that the local economy, hampered by continued layoffs in the aerospace 
industry, has shaken off all of its lingering ills. 
</P>
<P>
 Orange County consumers "are not as confident in the local scene as the 
national scene," pollster Katz said. The local confidence rating of 89 compared 
to a national rating of 92, a reverse of the late 1980s, when Orange County 
consistently scored higher than the rest of the nation. 
</P>
<P>
 The latest poll found that median annual household income was unchanged from 
last year at $47,000. That is a sharp contrast with the 1980s, when the median 
income rose 25% during the decade, compared to 6% nationally, said Baldassare, 
UCI's chairman of urban and regional planning in its School of Social Ecology. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's why our consumer confidence ratings were so high during that period," 
he said Thursday. "Until we start to see income grow again, we'll probably lag 
behind or stay on par with the national average." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, the report showed that 40% of the Orange County residents surveyed said 
they are better off now than they were a year earlier. That compared to just 
30% in the 1993 poll. 
</P>
<P>
 The pollsters, who interviewed 1,000 adults between Aug. 19 and 29, say the 
results have an error margin of plus or minus 3%. 
</P>
<P>
 Recent economic indicators also encourage optimism. In August, for instance, 
the county's jobless rate fell a full percentage point to 5.9% compared to 
July. And TRW Redi Property Data recently reported that sales of new and 
existing homes were up 26.2% for the first eight months of 1994, compared to 
the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
 "We all know hard economic numbers have been moving up for a few months now, 
and non-agricultural employment has been going up," said Cal State Fullerton 
economist Anil Puri. "But a big factor in any recovery has to be consumer 
spending." 
</P>
<P>
 During the recession, spending fell faster than personal income, meaning that 
people had dollars but were afraid to use them on consumer purchases. Now, Puri 
said, they are poised for a buying spree. 
</P>
<P>
 The survey found that the optimism is spread across all age groups and through 
every sector of the county. It found that 49% of Orange County consumers 
believe good times are ahead for the country over the next 12 months, compared 
to 29% in last year's survey. 
</P>
<P>
 They also believe the good times will be long-lasting, with 43% saying that 
the economy will remain healthy over five years. Last year, only 31% were so 
optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
 Times correspondent Hope Hamashige contributed to this report. Optimism 
Returns to O.C. Consumers 
</P>
<P>
 Orange County residents are more upbeat about the economy than they have been 
in five years. The Confidence Index is calculated by computing scores from a 
national and local survey and adjusting from the base year, 1966, when the 
national index was 100. Here's how the United States and Orange County compare: 
Big-Ticket Buys 
</P>
<P>
 The outlook for consumer spending has also improved, with the percentage 
saying this is a good time to make a major purchase highest since 1989. 
</P>
<P>
 About the big things that people buy for their homes, such as furniture, a 
refrigerator, a stove, television and things like that -- generally speaking, 
do you think now is a good time or a bad time for people to buy major household 
items? 
</P>
<P>
 1994: 
</P>
<P>
 Good time: 60% 
</P>
<P>
 Bad time: 25% 
</P>
<P>
 Don't know: 15% 
</P>
<P>
 Percentage saying "good time": 
</P>
<P>
 1994: 60% More Confident, but Cautious 
</P>
<P>
 County consumers are decidedly more confident about their financial situation 
than they were a year ago. And while they remain basically optimistic about the 
future, their view of the next 12 months is unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
 Would you say you (and your family) are financially better off or worse off 
than you were a year ago? 
</P>
<P>
